    <div align="left" id="post_message_527995"><div align="center" style="margin:5px; margin-top:5px; ">
<table width="85%" border="0" align="center" cellpadding="5" cellspacing="0" bgcolor="#333333" class="bbcodeQUOTE">
  
    <td width="30" align="center" valign="middle"><img src="/forums/images/openq.gif" width="30" height="30" ></td>
    <td>
		<div align="left" style="font-size: 12px; color: #999999; font-family: Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif;">Geeze, no wonder you're worried about the amount of content - you're devouring the game. I see you went the Neoshaman route.</div>
		</td>
    <td width="30" align="center" valign="middle"><img src="/forums/images/closeq.gif" width="30" height="30" align="right"></td>
  </tr>
</table>
</div>I'm only doing a couple of hours during the week days...but yeah, I'm putting in ~8 hours on the weekends. And that's with all the backtracking trying to complete bugged quests, trying to get dungeon groups....<br />
<br />
Unfortunately the game is very...questable. I find myself plowing through anything that's not an investigation. I'm definitely a &quot;stop and smell the roses&quot; kind of guy....but even doing that I feel like I'm flying through the game. <br />
<br />
I'm starting to drift away from Neoshaman. Chaos is nice for tanking and some burst DPS but generally I don't find a lot of use for the other things Chaos does in a solo capacity. (Which seems to be a metric **** ton of Dodge passives and actives.) I'm really only still using Chaos for two inner circle abilities...Escalation for quick aoe and builder....and Call of Eris for a finisher that does 270ish with a single resource...and up to 500 with 5.<br />
<br />
So I'm debating moving to another weapon for solo DPS. Really though Blood provides most of what I feel I need as far as DPS goes. Maybe I'll pick up something purely defensive, so I can take packs of 4+ without flinching. Active healing without +heal gear seems to be a lost cause.<br />
<br />
BTW, there's a setting in the .ini file that can disable all the questing markers and guide points. If you're looking for the real DIY questing experience, might want to turn that off. I can't imagine how hard it would be to figure out some stuff without it though. It can be super challenging already depending on how much info was provided for the quest, or what form that info takes.</div>
    <!-- / message -->
    
    
